The antidepressant drugs C-Pram S 10, Serta 25, Pari 10, and Fludac 10 are named Esci, Serta, Pari, and Flu. The tablets are dissolved in deionized water. The emission wavelength of Tyrosine-GQDs (10 × 10−6 M) in deionized water is found to be at 491 nm upon exciting with the wavelength of 398 nm. When the increasing volume of the drugs Esci, Serta, Pari, and Flu are individually added into the Tyrosine-GQDs, the emission intensity of Tyrosine-GQDs starts to decrease gradually. The fluorescence titration of the drugs vs Tyrosine-GQDs is very clear that there is no significant change in the emission intensity of the Tyrosine-GQDs after the addition of 100 μL of the Esci, Serta, Pari, and Flu drugs in Fig. 3a, b, c and d correspondingly. However, the titration is continued up to the addition of 150 μL to observe the saturation trend (Fig. SI2). The interaction and the complex formation between the Tyrosine-GQDs and the drugs can also be confirmed by the arise of new peaks at 439, 460, and 540 nm in the titration spectrum whereas, these new peaks are absent in the fluorescence emission spectrum of the pure drugs (Fig. SI3). In the titration spectrum of all the drugs, the blue shift in the wavelength (491 to 485 nm) is observed as the volume of the drugs increases [48] which indicates that the drug is forming a complex with the Tyrosine-GQDs. It is interesting to note a new peak at 439 nm which confirms the non-fluorescent ground state complex formation between the drug and the Tyrosine-GQDs [40]. Additionally, Esci (8 H-bonds), Serta (1 H-bonds), Pari (5 H-bonds), and Flu (5 H-bonds) have the propensity to accept H-bonds from the GQDs. Additionally, GQDs are rich in electrons, due to the presence of the O, N, and π electron system of the graphene moiety. As the electronegative Cl, F, and O are present in the drug molecules, they are electron acceptors through which H-bonds are formed. The presence of high electronegative atoms (F, Cl, O) present at the surface of the drug compounds has a high tendency to be involved in the formation of H-bonding. The addition of the SSRI drugs into the Tyrosine-GQDs solution, the presence of -COOH, and -NH groups at the surface of GQDs tends to form H-bonds due to the dipole-dipole attraction [49]. Fig. 4
                         demonstrates the hydrogen bond formation between the Tyrosine-GQDs and SSRI drugs. The π electron cloud in GQDs is likely to promote the formation of H-bonding. The development of H-bonding shortens the distance between the GQDs interlayers, lowering their emission intensity and quenching their fluorescence in the process [48]. Further, the fluorescence lifetime measurements also confirm the formation of intermolecular hydrogen bonding and non-radiative decay of the excited state electron before they return to the ground state [43,50]. The addition of 150 μL of SSRI drugs into the 2 mL of Tyrosine-GQDs aqueous solution increases the lifetime of the Tyrosine-GQDs without changing the functionality (i.e., 3 exponential decay) (Table 4
                        ). The lifetime value of Tyrosine-GQDs is 2.46 nm, which increased to 3.24, 3.71, 3.67, and 4.41 ns upon the addition of Esci, Serta, Pari, and Flu respectively [43] (Fig. 5
                        ). The quenching rate constants also prove that the complexes formed Tyrosine-GQDs∙Esci, Tyrosine-GQDs∙Serta, Tyrosine-GQDs∙Pari, and Tyrosine-GQDs∙Flu are ground-state complexes with the loss of fluorescence. Further, the quenching rate constant for Pari and Flu is double the order of the quenching rate constant observed for Esci and Serta (Table 5
                        ).
